My first Oktoberfest
Ballermann apres-ski hits on endless loop, beer from litre jugs and celebrities in designer dirndls.
A Wiesn debut.
Susanne Kronzucker and I don't really have much in common.
She is blond, a television presenter and wears a custom-made dirndl.
I have dark hair, am a student and my dress is second-hand.
But there is one thing we have in common: barely three minutes at the Wiesn and the photographers are already pouncing on us and snapping away on the memory cards - very flattering, and on my first visit to the Wiesn.
That's how you make friends.
The cheap dirndl seems to serve its purpose.
As a Wiesn tourist and actually resident north of the Weißwurstäquator, the feeling of well-being in traditional costume has so far been limited.
But once you arrive at the Theresienwiese, everything is half as bad.
Almost everyone wears dirndl or lederhosen; no one looks disgusted or embarrassed - everything is completely normal.
Only my dirndl apron gets strange looks at the chocolate banana stand.
A Munich woman points out that I've tied the apron wrong: "Left hoast frei, middle Jungfrau, right vergeben, hinten verwitwet."
I secretly frieze my bow from the back to the left.
"Fits," she says and laughs.
Others make less fuss about subtle flirting techniques and wear plain felt hats that say "To drunk to get dressed!" and stick out their bare backsides at you uninvited.
The young man with the exhibitionist attitudes is called Bob, comes from England and is also visiting the Oktoberfest for the first time.
He finds it "gorgeous," with a long drawn-out "ooooo."
That's what he tells me after he's finished his previously drunk Maß.
Right next to one of those hydrants that everyone thinks is a rubbish bin.
So Bob is one of those notorious "wild beasts."
Others are not lucky enough to get rid of alcohol in this way.
Around eight o'clock in the evening, paramedics run through the fairground in droves to take care of the poor saps.
The orderlies always appear in a pack - four at a time dragging a covered stretcher from tent to tent.
It works like with most Wiesn visitors: empty there, full back again.
You can't see who is lying in the coffin under the tarpaulin.
"They're the ones who never pack," one of the paramedics called out to me when asked and disappeared into the crowd.
