Dark matter influences flight of space probes
For years, a mysterious phenomenon has perplexed researchers: dark matter influences the speed of space probes during so-called swing-by manoeuvres.
Experts fear that Albert Einstein's general theory of relativity may not be entirely correct.
The space probe "Ulysses" flew through space for almost 18 years.
Because of soon freezing fuel lines, it is now threatened with death from cold.
For years, a mysterious phenomenon has been causing confusion among scientists - the swing-by anomaly.
Swing-by is a flight manoeuvre of space probes in which they gain extra momentum in the gravitational field of a celestial body, such as the Earth.
This allows the probes to save a lot of fuel.
The European-American research probe Cassini-Huygens used this physical trick, as did the solar probe Ulysses.
What has puzzled researchers for years, however, is this: The spacecraft do not behave 100 per cent as one would expect according to the time-honoured law of gravity.
Rather, there are irregularities in the speed.
The probes unexpectedly speed up or slow down.
Until now, physicists have been unable to explain this effect.
They dubbed it the swing-by anomaly.
Some experts fear that even Albert Einstein's general theory of relativity, which describes the gravitational pull of matter through a curvature of space, may not be entirely correct.
American physicist Stephen Adler of the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton still firmly believes that Einstein was not wrong and tries to explain the swing-by anomaly with the help of so-called dark matter that astronomers have identified in the universe.
"Dark matter could be responsible for the anomaly, which could also be located very close to the Earth," he writes.
Space researchers have only known about the existence of dark matter for about ten years.
It obviously exerts an attractive force, the effect of which on other celestial bodies can be observed.
However, dark matter itself is completely invisible, i.e. it neither emits nor reflects any electromagnetic radiation, especially no visible light.
According to scientists' calculations, dark matter accounts for a good fifth of the total mass of the universe.
Tourists kidnapped in Egypt are free
After ten days in the hands of their kidnappers, the tourists kidnapped in Egypt are said to be free again, as the Italian Foreign Minister confirmed.
The kidnappers from Sudan had demanded a ransom of several million euros.
Six kidnappers were reportedly killed in a shootout before the release.
Five Germans have been kidnapped in southern Egypt.
Ransom negotiations are said to be underway.
Again and again, Germans are targeted by kidnappers.
WELT ONLINE describes the most important cases.
The European tourists kidnapped in the Sahara are apparently free.
This was reported by Egyptian state television, the Arabic TV station Al-Arabija and Italian media.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini confirmed the release, according to reports on Italian TV station Sky TG 24: "Our fellow citizens and the other hostages have been freed.
We are currently checking their state of health," Frattini said.
The five Germans, five Italians and one Romanian as well as their eight Egyptian companions are well and safe, Egyptian state television reported.
The 19 participants of a desert expedition are said to be already on their way to Cairo.
The background of a shootout before the release of the hostages remains unclear: According to an Egyptian security official, the kidnappers were ready to end the kidnapping before the Sudanese army surprisingly killed six of the kidnappers.
"The problem was solved.
They agreed to a ransom," the official said.
It had been "just a matter of receiving the hostages" when suddenly "this surprise" came.
Sudanese soldiers had shot six of the kidnappers and arrested two of them in the border area between Sudan, Chad and Egypt on Sunday.
The kidnappers had demanded a ransom of six million euros from Germany; the money was to be handed over by the German wife of one of the hostages.
The daily newspaper "El Masri El Jom" reported, citing a German mediator, that the release of the hostages was delayed because the kidnappers feared for their safety.
According to the report, the kidnappers want to release the female hostages after paying the ransom.
The men were to be held until the kidnappers had a safe escape route.
The German embassy in Cairo declined to comment on the report.
